# Android Compose App Rules

Use these rules when building or modifying Android apps with Jetpack Compose.

## Compose UI

- Prefer stateless composables where possible.
- Hoist state to the lowest stable owner that needs it.
- Keep composables small and focused.
- Do not perform blocking work in composables.
- Do not create expensive objects repeatedly inside recomposition.
- Use stable keys for lazy lists.
- Provide empty, loading, success, and error states for real data flows.
- Use Material components consistently unless a custom design system exists.

## State and ViewModels

- Use ViewModels for screen-level state.
- Expose immutable UI state from ViewModels.
- Use `StateFlow`/`Flow` for observable state.
- Collect state using lifecycle-aware APIs.
- Do not expose mutable state directly from ViewModels.
- Keep business logic out of composables.
- Keep repositories/data sources testable.

## Dependency Management

- If the app does not use Hilt/Koin/Dagger, use explicit factories or a small service locator.
- Initialize shared dependencies before screens render.
- Do not instantiate databases or repositories repeatedly in composables.
- Avoid hidden global mutable state unless explicitly part of the app architecture.

## Navigation

- Keep route definitions centralized.
- Avoid stringly-typed route duplication.
- Validate navigation arguments.
- Do not leave placeholder routes or dead screens.
- Back behavior should match Android expectations.

## Persistence

- Use Room/DataStore/files according to the data type.
- Do not fake persistence with local-only UI state.
- Migrations must preserve user data.
- Avoid destructive migrations without explicit approval.
- Do not run database work on the main thread.

## Permissions

- Request permissions only when needed.
- Explain permission purpose in-product before system prompts.
- Handle denied and permanently denied states.
- Do not assume permissions are granted.
- Keep manifest permissions minimal.

## Build and Release

- Keep Gradle configuration consistent.
- Do not mix incompatible Android Gradle Plugin, Kotlin, Compose Compiler, and SDK versions.
- Do not commit generated build outputs or local signing secrets.
- Verify debug builds with `assembleDebug`.
- Verify release builds separately when release behavior matters.

## Quality Gate

Before considering Android work complete:

- `./gradlew assembleDebug` passes.
- Relevant unit tests pass if present.
- App launches on device/emulator when runtime behavior changed.
- Screens have real state, not hardcoded mock-only flows.
- Permissions are minimal and handled.
- No dead buttons, placeholder routes, or fake toggles remain in touched flows.
